# Development guidelines

## General

- Use the GitHub CLI (`gh`) for all GitHub-related tasks when possible
- Be sure to typecheck and lint when you’re done making a series of code changes

When importing types in React, prefer `import { type TypeName } from React;` over using `React.TypeName` in the code.

## Commit guidelines

Use conventional commit messages following this pattern:

```
<type>[optional scope]: <description>

[optional body]
```

- Prefer `feat` and `fix` for the type, but other types are allowed including `build`, `chore`, `ci`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `perf`, and `test`.
- Use a concise lowercase scope when appropriate, but most commits don't need one. For example, `fix(varnish): don't throttle shopify webhooks`.
- The description starts lowercase (unless it begins with an acronym or proper noun) and uses the imperative tense, not the passive tense. For example, "add Polish language" instead of "adds Polish language".
- The first line must be 50 characters or less.
- Trivial changes don't need a body (e.g. `fix: --help typo`).
- When there is a body, lead with the motivation: explain why the change is needed, not just what it does. Keep it brief, in complete sentences.
- Cite evidence in the body when it exists: Slack thread links, Sentry issue links, related PRs, API docs, and commit hashes (e.g. "The only usage was removed in 66f417fce92"). Bare URLs on their own line are fine.

**Example commit with body**:

```
fix: log shopify webhooks in the background

Fix a problem where bursts of webhooks from the Matrixify app caused so
many writes per second that DB replication could fall behind by hours.

https://ifixit.slack.com/archives/C09FMSNS1/p1780528407434489
```

## Pull request guidelines

When writing pull requests, follow these guidelines:

- Title should be in sentence case (first word and proper nouns capitalized), without a conventional commit type prefix. For example, "Log shopify webhooks in the background".
- A `Component:` prefix is welcome when it adds clarity, with the description still capitalized after it. For example, "DHL: Split combined tracking numbers on `<BR>`" or "Locale picker: Handle unpublished route locales".
- Start the body with a bulleted list of references when they exist, using full URLs rather than bare issue numbers (full URLs also work across repos):
  - `- close https://github.com/iFixit/ifixit/issues/62287` if the PR closes the issue
  - `- connect https://github.com/iFixit/ifixit/issues/62154` if related but not fully resolving it
  - Other reference styles as appropriate: `- fix a bug from <PR url>`, `- built on top of <PR url>`, `- followup to <PR url>`, `- resolve [SENTRY-ID](<sentry url>)`, or just a bare `- <slack/PR url>` when the relationship is obvious
- The description should briefly explain the change and its motivation. Link supporting evidence such as Slack threads and Sentry issues. Small changes can get away with a single sentence or even just a link.
- Link relevant API or vendor documentation, often as a bulleted `### Docs` subsection.
- Use `##` sections when they earn their keep: `## Changes` (bulleted changeset, with per-app `###` subsections if the PR spans apps), `## Motivation`, `## QA` (manual QA steps), `## On deploy` (commands in code blocks, or a `- [ ]` checklist of manual steps).

**Example PR body**:

````
- close https://github.com/iFixit/ifixit/issues/62287

Brief description of the change and its motivation.

https://ifixit.slack.com/archives/C09FMSNS1/p1781024024937349

